I think useReducer and useState both work in your situation. but useState might be easier here. There is no complex logic or sideEffect involved, we don&#39;t have to utilize useReducer here.

    const [open, setOpen] = useState({ADD_PROFILE:false,EDIT_PROFILE:false});

    setOpen({...open, ADD_PROFILE:!open.ADD_PROFILE})

    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt; AddProfileDialog open={open.ADD_PROFILE}/&gt;
      &lt; EditProfileDialog open={open.EDIT_PROFILE}/&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

However, both useReducer and useState will cause the state change, every time we open a new Dialog, all the Opened dialogs will still reRender. You may want to use React.memo is your child component is too complex.

You can do something like this and You can add a cancel action.

```
const [isOpen, dispatch] = useReducer((state, action) =&gt; {
        switch (action.type) {
            case &#39;ADD_PROFILE&#39;:
                return { ...state, ADD_PROFILE: true, EDIT_PROFILE: false }
            case &#39;EDIT_PROFILE&#39;:
                return { ...state, EDIT_PROFILE: false, ADD_PROFILE: false }
            case &#39;CANCEL&#39;:
                return {...state, EDIT_PROFILE: false, ADD_PROFILE: false }
            default:
                return state
        }
    }, [])
```

